    {
      "id": 16350,
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 65360,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A live vaccine is a vaccine that contains a killed virus, and it is safe for all children</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 65361,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A live vaccine is a vaccine that contains a weakened or attenuated virus, and it is safe for most children</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 65362,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A live vaccine is a vaccine that contains a live virus, and it is not recommended for any child</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 65363,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A live vaccine is a vaccine that contains both live and killed virus, and it is safe for most children, but not recommended for children with weakened immune systems</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A mother visits the pediatric clinic for her 2-year-old child&#39;s routine check-up. During the visit, she expresses concerns about the scheduled administration of a live vaccine. As the pediatrician, how would you explain what a live vaccine is, and what safety guidance would you provide regarding these vaccines?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8350726",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32986,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B)</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>A live vaccine is a vaccine that contains a weakened or attenuated virus, and it is safe for most children.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Live vaccines use a weakened </strong>(attenuated) <strong>form of the germ that causes a disease</strong>. These vaccines are <strong>closely related to the natural infection </strong>that they <strong>help prevent </strong>and <strong>create a strong and long-lasting immune response</strong>. They are generally <strong>safe for most children</strong>; however, they are not recommended for children with certain health conditions, particularly those that affect the immune system, because the weakened virus may still cause disease in these individuals.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. This statement is <strong>incorrect </strong>as <strong>live vaccines do not contain a killed virus</strong>; that would be an inactivated vaccine.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This statement is <strong>misleading</strong>. <strong>Live vaccines do contain a live virus</strong>, but it is attenuated and safe for most children, not all.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This statement is <strong>partially correct </strong>but is <strong>misleading </strong>in suggesting that <strong>live vaccines can contain both live and killed viruses</strong>. While live vaccines are safe for most children, they are indeed not recommended for children with weakened immune systems.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Live vaccines</strong>, such as <strong>MMR, varicella, and rotavirus, </strong>are generally <strong>safe for most children </strong>but may not be suitable for those with certain medical conditions or compromised immune systems, who could face serious complications from vaccine-preventable diseases</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">-</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition page 739</strong></span></span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 65361,
      "solution_audio": null,
      "solution_video": null,
